Lithium polymer batteries are a special type of lithium ion battery. This means that no lithium metal is present in either type of batteries. The energy is stored because Lithium ions (Li+) are wedged between graphite sheets, which don't like it being there, which is high in energy. If you release the ions back, they release the energy, they shuttle back into the Iron Manganese oxide material, and electrons are pushed into the external circuit. The guys who invented this groundbreaking battery got the Nobel prize last year (Goodenough, Whittingham, Yoshino).
